george pattison the heart could never speak reflections on language in an age of technology george pattison the heart could never speak reflections on language in an age of technology george pattison lady margaret professor of divinity oxford university lecture the heart could never speak reflections on language in an age of technology taking its cue from the poem the heart could never speak by edwin muir the lecture explores the heart's need of speech in an age when speaking is inhibited not only by the artefactuality of technological communications media discussed by derrida and heidegger but also by the personal and moral challenges addressed by kierkegaard and dostoevsky co sponsored by the stanford humanities center and philosophy and literature stanford free and open to the public more information date and time tuesday january 12 2010 5 15 pm approximate duration of 1.25 hour s location levinthal hall stanford humanities center near tressider 424 santa teresa street stanford ca 94305 map audience faculty staff alumni friends general public students category lectures readings sponsor department of religious studies & in cooperation with the stanford humanities center and philosophy literature stanford contact 723 2895 pitkin stanford edu download add to personal calendar vcal record email event print use this permalink last modified january 8 2010
